      <hedline>
        <hl1>Why Do Boys Kill?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Carole Chervin says Sept 7 article on FBI's caution signs for violence in classroom ignores most obvious trait of violent criminals: maleness; says study must be made to find why one sex is so much more prone to killing than other</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''F.B.I. Lists Caution Signs for Violence in Classroom'' (news article, Sept. 7):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''F.B.I. Lists Caution Signs for Violence in Classroom'' (news article, Sept. 7):</p>
        <p>You write that an F.B.I. report says ''there is no research that has identified traits and characteristics that can reliably distinguish school shooters from other students.'' The F.B.I.'s report ignores the single most obvious trait of all of these criminals: maleness.</p>
        <p>I agree with Attorney General Janet Reno's warning that threat assessment studies must not be used to unfairly label or stigmatize children, but neither should we ignore the obvious. We have much to gain by studying what it is about boys and girls and how we bring them up that makes one sex so much more prone to killing than the other.</p>
        <p>Only then may we apply what we learn toward changing behavior and ultimately reducing crime.</p>
        <p>CAROLE CHERVIN  New York, Sept. 8, 2000</p>
      </block>
